04827nam a22007095i 9781478007333DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019981093  a97814780073337 a10.1515/97814780073332doi  a(DE-B1597)553495  a(OCoLC)1198924450  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aHM851 4aHM851b.S535 2020 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a306.209552231 aShakhsari, Sima, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics of Rightful Killing :bCivil Society, Gender, and Sexuality in Weblogistan /cSima Shakhsari. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- t[ 1 ]. Weblogistan and the Iranian Diaspora -- t[ 2 ]. Civil Society (jaame'e-ye madani), Soccer, and Gendered Politics in Weblogistan -- t[ 3 ]. Whores, Homos, and Feminists -- t[ 4 ]. Weblogistan and Its Homosexual Problem -- t[ 5 ]. The War Machine, Neoliberal Homo OEconomicus, and the Experts -- t[ Coda ] Revolutionary Ends -- t[ Appendix ]. Statement by Iranian Bloggers on Hossein Derakhshan -- t[ Notes ] -- t[ References ] -- t[ Index ]0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 2000s, mainstream international news outlets celebrated the growth of Weblogistan-the online and real-life transnational network of Iranian bloggers-and depicted it as a liberatory site that gave voice to Iranians. As Sima Shakhsari argues in Politics of Rightful Killing, the common assumptions of Weblogistan as a site of civil society consensus and resistance to state oppression belie its deep internal conflicts. While Weblogistan was an effective venue for some Iranians to "practice democracy," it served as a valuable site for the United States to surveil bloggers and express anti-Iranian sentiment and policies. At the same time, bloggers used the network to self-police and enforce gender and sexuality norms based on Western liberal values in ways that unwittingly undermined Weblogistan's claims of democratic participation. In this way, Weblogistan became a site of cybergovernmentality, where biopolitical security regimes disciplined and regulated populations. Analyzing online and off-line ethnography, Shakhsari provides an account of digital citizenship that raises questions about the internet's relationship to political engagement, militarism, and democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aBlogsxPolitical aspectszIran. 0aBlogsxSocial aspectszIran. 0aCivil societyzIran. 0aCyberspacexPolitical aspectszIran. 0aCyberspacexSocial aspectszIran. 0aPolitical participationzIranxComputer network resources. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069631808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007333zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007333423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007333.jpg  a978-3-11-069631-8  DUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2